question: What are AMD's strategic priorities for AI as of late 2024?
ground_truth: AMD is focusing on expanding its Instinct data center GPU portfolio (specifically MI300), enhancing the ROCm software stack to compete with CUDA, and driving adoption across cloud and enterprise markets.
generated_answer:
AMD's AI strategy in 2024 centered on aggressive MI300 deployment, software ecosystem expansion, and broadening customer engagements beyond hyperscalers.
2024: Execution Year
The year began with MI300 qualification ramps. Lisa Su noted in Q1 2024: "The MI300 ramp is going really well. If we look at just what's happened over the last 90 days, we've been working very closely with our customers to qualify MI300 in their production data centers, both from a hardware standpoint, software standpoint." The focus was establishing production credibility with major cloud customers.
By mid-year, monetization accelerated with sequential revenue growth. Q2 2024 commentary emphasized workload diversification: "We're very happy with how MI300 has progressed. When we started the year, I think the key point for us was to get our products into our customers' data centers, to have them qualify their workloads, to really ramp in production."
Q3 2024 marked both product transition and customer expansion. Su stated: "Our customer engagements are actually broadening quite well. So, certainly, cloud -- our largest cloud customers are broadening the set of workloads that they're running on AMD Instinct. And we're also very engaged with a number of large cloud and enterprise customers that are actively working with us." The MI325 launch in Q4 signaled continued roadmap execution.
Software investment emerged as a strategic priority, with analysts probing what Su acknowledged as "a big challenge" alongside hardware scaling.
